        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 13-year-old girl from the Czech Republic who is brought to clinic because teachers and family have noticed marked distractibility and trouble staying focused on school tasks [SNOMED:F90.0]. She often starts homework but leaves it unfinished, misses details, and needs repeated redirection because of a cognitive deficit in attention [SNOMED:F90.0]. Her parents also describe emotional impulsivity, with quick reactions and difficulty pausing before speaking or acting when frustrated [SNOMED:F90.0].\n\nAt school, {patientName} is bright and socially engaged, but her day is shaped by inconsistent attention and variable executive functioning, so she loses track of instructions and struggles to organize assignments despite wanting to do well [SNOMED:F90.0]. She enjoys drawing, listening to music, and chatting with friends after school, but even during activities she likes, she can become distracted and jump from one task to another [SNOMED:F90.0].\n\nAt home, she lives with her parents and a younger sibling in an urban setting in CZ. Her mother says {patientName} is caring and expressive, but emotionally reactive at times, especially during homework or chores, which can lead to arguments followed by regret [SNOMED:F90.0]. She has no dramatic physical complaints today and appears generally healthy, but she fidgets in her chair, looks around the room frequently, and needs questions repeated because her attention drifts [SNOMED:F90.0]."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:5887b02f-8b2a-4178-8552-385135e982f5",
